<subSubSection pageId="26" pageNumber="1029" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="26.[813,1420,724,884]" lastBlockId="26.[168,776,1069,1429]" pageId="26" pageNumber="1029">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[850,980,724,748]" pageId="26" pageNumber="1029">Comments.</emphasis>
This is a frequent species in the study area. It grows in full sunlight conditions in deep to moderately deep soils or in deep cracks on grassland slopes. It can be recognized by its densely glandular hairs, entire or dentate leaf margin and 
<quantity box="[1070,1184,859,883]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.45" metricValueMax="1.5" metricValueMin="1.4" pageId="26" pageNumber="1029" unit="mm" value="14.5" valueMax="15.0" valueMin="14.0">14–15 mm</quantity>
tall involucre. and yellow tubular disc florets disposed in cymose-cor- ymb inflorescences at the end of the branches; phylla- ries densely covered with white tomentose hairs. Fruits: achenes with sericeous pubescent surface and white pappus.
</paragraph>
<caption box="[168,684,1001,1021]" pageId="26" pageNumber="1029" startId="26.[168,230,1001,1021]" targetBox="[168,775,611,976]" targetPageId="26">
